# {{ .prefix }}-executing-plans

<!-- awf:section positioning -->
The `implementation` chain node, inline shape. Wraps `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}` step 6 ("Implementation") when a plan exists and the agent has determined that tasks are tightly coupled or sequential. Companion to `{{ .prefix }}-subagent-driven-development`. Inline execution suits tightly coupled tasks, but length and parent-context pressure are explicit reasons to run a long plan through the subagent-per-task companion where the runtime supports it.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section when-to-invoke -->
## When to invoke

Invoke when:
- A plan exists under `{{ .layout.plansDir }}/YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>.md`, AND
- Plan tasks are tightly coupled or sequential: state flows between tasks, each task informs the next, or the plan is short enough that subagent-per-task overhead is not justified, AND
- Full main-session visibility into each step is valuable (debugging, exploratory iteration, or work that may need mid-flight redirection).

The agent picks between this skill and `{{ .prefix }}-subagent-driven-development` by inspecting the plan's phase structure and task coupling. For plans whose tasks are mostly independent and benefit from fresh context per task, use `{{ .prefix }}-subagent-driven-development` instead.

If no plan exists, implement directly without a plan workflow, then {{ if .targetWorkflowRouter }}call `awf_workflow` alone with `skill: "reviewing-impl"`{{ else }}invoke `{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-impl`{{ end }} at the end.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

<!-- awf:section procedure-resolve-plan -->
1. **Resolve the plan path.** Use the most-recent mutable plan under `{{ .layout.plansDir }}/` that this chain run is implementing, or the path the user passes explicitly. A plan is mutable while its own `status:` frontmatter is `Proposed` and freezes when that flips to `Implemented`, independent of any linked ADR's status.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-raise-concerns -->
2. **Read the plan, raise concerns before starting.** Surface critical gaps to the user before touching code: missing file content, unclear commands, contradictory steps, or placeholders ("TBD", "similar to task N"). Do not guess.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-per-task -->
3. **Per task, execute, validate, commit (one commit per task):**
   - **Implement** following the plan's exact file paths, content, and diff. No drift from the plan; raise to the user if the plan needs an amendment.
   - **Validate.** Stage the complete transaction, run `awf check --staged`, then run {{ with .vars.gateCmd }}`{{ . }}`{{ else }}the project's gate{{ end }} (fast tier). Commit only after both commands pass. The hook repeats the staged check as defense in depth. See `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}` for the tier split and when to run the full tier.
   - **Commit.** Use Conventional Commits (`<type>(<scope>): <subject>`), keep the subject under 72 chars, and explain the *why* in the body. When this task applies some frozen V2 ADR operations, append the next Applied event and stage exactly the matching claim mutations in this same checked commit; do not wait for one final all-operation commit. Auto-commit when green (tests pass + lint clean).
   - **Checkpoint.** After each independently resumable committed and reviewed task, run the complete routine protocol below before starting the next task.

<!-- awf:include checkpoint-routine -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section tdd-opt-in -->
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section gate-tier-detail -->
{{ if .data.e2eSuitePaths }}   **Gate tiers:** fast tier ({{ with .vars.gateCmd }}`{{ . }}`{{ else }}the project's gate{{ end }}) is the default.{{ with .vars.gateCmdFull }} Run `{{ . }}` when the regression test lives in a pre-push-only surface:{{ end }}{{ range .data.e2eSuitePaths }} `{{ .path }}`{{ end }}. The fast tier does not exercise those surfaces. See `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}`.
{{ end }}<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-adr-final-commit -->
4. **Final commit for ADR-driven plans.** Flip the plan's own `status:` from Proposed to Implemented and record implementation findings. For a V2 ADR, append its final Applied batch and matching claim mutations before the Implemented event, or use the direct implicit transition when all operations land together; if execution stops, append Abandoned and leave prior Applied effects intact while the remainder becomes Canceled. A plan may instead leave a reviewed ADR Accepted when implementation has not started. Then run `{{ with .vars.activeMdRegenCmd }}{{ . }}{{ else }}awf sync{{ end }}` to regenerate `{{ .layout.indexMd }}` and stage it; the commit touches the decisions directory, so the gate's drift test must pass.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-non-adr-final-commit -->
5. **Final commit for non-ADR plans.** Flip the plan's own `status:` frontmatter from `Proposed → Implemented`, recording any implementation findings in the plan's Notes section, the same freeze as ADR-driven plans, keyed on the plan's own status.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section terminal-step -->
6. **Terminal step:** {{ if .targetWorkflowRouter }}call `awf_workflow` alone with `skill: "reviewing-impl"`.{{ else }}invoke `{{ .prefix }}-reviewing-impl` via the project's skill-invocation mechanism.{{ end }} That skill dispatches an implementation-review subagent against the current-session SHA range, routes the findings by the agent's classification, and applies fixes as new commits on top.

<!-- awf:include checkpoint-routine -->
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section project-invariants -->
- **Expected output is non-negotiable.** Never adjust an expected/golden value to make a test pass; fix the cause or the test's premise.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section notes-gate -->
- Gates are mandatory; if red, fix the root cause. Do not bypass with `--no-verify` except in genuine emergencies, and follow up with a fix commit.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section notes-auto-commit -->
- Auto-commit when green: tests pass + lint clean → commit without asking.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section notes-one-concern -->
- One concern per commit; if a task accumulates unrelated tweaks, split it.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section notes-docs-travel -->
- Docs travel with the change: any commit that changes reality updates the corresponding docs or `AGENTS.md` in the same commit.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section red-flags -->
## Red flags

These thoughts mean stop. You're rationalizing:

| Rationalization | Reality |
|---|---|
| "These two tasks are small, one commit is fine." | One commit per task. Batching hides which change did what and breaks bisection. |
| "The plan step is slightly off, I'll adjust it." | No silent drift. Raise the amendment to the user first. |
| "The gate failure looks unrelated, commit anyway." | Gates are mandatory. Fix the root cause; no `--no-verify`. |
| "I'll update the docs in a follow-up commit." | Docs travel with the change: the same commit that makes them true. |
<!-- awf:end -->
